---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { LINKS } from '../components/siteConfig';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="ExNulla — Systems Architecture"
  description="Systems architecture, public proof-of-work, and deterministic execution."
  active=""
>
  <div class="kicker">ExNulla</div>
  <h1 class="h1">I build systems that can survive contact with reality.</h1>

  <p class="sub">
    ExNulla is where I prove how I think: constraints first, architecture before noise, and delivery
    that can be inspected instead of merely claimed. This is not a brochure. It is a working proof
    surface.
  </p>

  <div class="btnrow">
    <a class="btn primary" href="/projects">View Projects</a>
    <a class="btn ghost" href="/cv">Read the CV</a>
    <a class="btn ghost" href="/lab">Open the Lab</a>
    <a class="btn ghost" href={LINKS.linkedin} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">LinkedIn</a>
  </div>

  <div class="hr"></div>

  <section class="grid grid-2">
    <div>
      <h2>Why this exists</h2>
      <p>
        I did not come into software through a normal lane. I came in the same way I built
        businesses: define the problem, map the constraints, design the system, ship the work, and
        improve what breaks.
      </p>
      <p>
        ExNulla is the public version of that operating model. The site, the case studies, the
        demos, the stream, and the surrounding funnel all serve one purpose: make the work visible
        enough that nobody has to guess what I can do.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>What you will find here</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>
          <strong>Projects:</strong> architecture decisions, trade-offs, and delivery discipline.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>CV:</strong> the operator behind the system, framed through execution rather than claims.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Lab:</strong> runnable proof where the ideas stop being theory.</li>
        <li>
          <strong>Meta:</strong> build/version provenance and the operating discipline behind the site.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="hr"></div>

  <section>
    <h2>Three ways to read ExNulla</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-3">
      <article class="card">
        <h2 style="font-size:18px; margin:0 0 8px">Architecture</h2>
        <p class="small" style="margin:0 0 12px">
          Case studies built to show reasoning, constraints, and the shape of the solution—not just
          the polished outcome.
        </p>
        <div class="btnrow">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="/projects">Open Projects</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h2 style="font-size:18px; margin:0 0 8px">Operator</h2>
        <p class="small" style="margin:0 0 12px">
          The digital CV explains the person behind the system: builder, operator, and developer
          architect moving in public.
        </p>
        <div class="btnrow">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="/cv">Open CV</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h2 style="font-size:18px; margin:0 0 8px">Proof</h2>
        <p class="small" style="margin:0 0 12px">
          The lab is where design becomes executable. Simulations are isolated, intentional, and
          shipped as proof—not as decoration.
        </p>
        <div class="btnrow">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="/lab">Open Lab</a>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="hr"></div>

  <section class="card">
    <div class="kicker">Featured case</div>
    <h2 style="margin-top:4px">Attest Pipeline</h2>
    <p>
      Deterministic identity attestation for hostile JSON ingestion, canonicalization, hashing, and
      cross-institution matching—without turning KYC into a long-term PII honeypot.
    </p>
    <p class="small">
      This is the kind of work I want to be known for: architecture that closes real abuse paths
      while reducing operational and data-risk surface area.
    </p>
    <div class="btnrow">
      <a class="btn ghost" href="/projects/attest-pipeline">View Case Study</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="hr"></div>

  <section class="grid grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Built in public, from zero</h2>
      <p class="small" style="margin:0 0 12px">
        The ExNulla ecosystem did not come from an existing employer, audience, or software career
        path. It was built from zero as a working system: brand, repos, site, demos, stream, and
        market-facing proof.
      </p>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Architecture, implementation, and delivery in the open.</li>
        <li>
          Public signal designed to compound: site, stream, social, and repos feeding each other.
        </li>
        <li>Proof-of-work first, credential story second.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Operating stance</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Start with limits, not features.</li>
        <li>Prefer systems that are inspectable, testable, and cheap to recover.</li>
        <li>Use AI aggressively, but keep judgment and accountability human.</li>
        <li>Move fast where ambiguity is low; slow down where the architecture matters.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="small" style="margin-top:12px">
        I am not trying to look like a conventional candidate. I am trying to be legible to the
        people who know what good systems work looks like.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="hr"></div>

  <section class="identity">
    <div class="identity-inner">
      <img src="/assets/James-Headshot.jpg" alt="James Huson" loading="lazy" />
      <div>
        <strong>James Huson</strong>
        <div class="small">Developer architecture, systems thinking, and public proof-of-work.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="btnrow" style="justify-content:center;">
      <a class="btn ghost" href={LINKS.linkedin} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">LinkedIn</a>
      <a class="btn ghost" href="https://github.com/Thesis-Web" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer"
        >GitHub</a
      >
      <a class="btn ghost" href={LINKS.kick} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Kick</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
